observations.recommendation:
a. the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the computation and recording of the Real Property Tax and Special Education Tax Receivables set up and the proper recognition of fines and penalties on property taxes are in accordance with the provisions of Sections 20 and 23, Chapter 3, Volume I of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System for Local Government Units and Sections 233 and 235 of Republic Act (RA) 7160;
b. the Municipal Accountant to rectify and reconstruct the incorrect entries made in CY 2019 on the set up of Real Property Taxes (RPT) and Special Education Taxes (SET) as guided by the correcting entries recommended by the Audit Team provided in Appendix 7;
c. the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer in the preparation of the necessary adjusting journal entries to exclude/remove the fines and penalties previously recorded as RPT and SET receivables and to identify the unrecorded collections from the PTO to arrive at the reconciled balances of the RPT and SET receivables;
d. the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the Provincial Treasurer’s Office (PTO) in securing the subsidiary ledger of all the Land Tax Dues collected from previous years up to the current year to update and record the RPT and SET collected in the books of the Municipality; and
e. Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to immediately coordinate with the PTO whenever the remittances of the latter vary with the records of the Municipality, in order that timely adjustments or corrections of affected accounts could be effected.

a. the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the reported balances in the Statement of Financial Position with the balances recorded in lapsing schedules; 
b. the General Services Officer and the Inventory Committee to conduct complete physical inventory of all PPE of the Municipality; and
c. the Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer to continue exerting efforts to reconcile the variances in their records.

a. require all Inventory Custodian to prepare and submit monthly report of inventories to the Accounting Office for proper recording of expenses and balances;
b. require all Inventory Stock Custodian and the Accounting Department to maintain supply stock cards and supply ledger cards, respectively, to account the receipt and disposition of inventory items and to facilitate reconciliation of both records; and
c. require the conduct of physical count of all inventory accounts and submit to the Audit Team the Report of Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) to establish accuracy, validity and existence of the recorded Inventories.

a. the Market Supervisor and Grand Terminal Supervisor to strictly enforce the provisions of the contract of lease of market stalls and the pertinent revenue code of the Municipality, especially on payments of rentals and the revocation of contracts and eviction of delinquent stallholders;
b. the Municipal Accountant to pass the necessary Journal Entry Voucher based on the submitted schedule of delinquent accounts in compliance with Section 112 of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and Section 7 of the International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS) No. 1, Volume I;
c. the Market and Grand Terminal Supervisors and Municipal Treasurer to consistently send demand/collection letters to delinquent Stallholders, and to recommend to proper Municipal authorities the termination of contracts of those who continuously refuse to comply with the demand for payments; and
d. the Market and Grand Terminal Supervisors and Municipal Treasurer to apply for bond in compliance with Treasury Circular No. 2009-002; and
e. the Municipal Accountant to maintain special accounts in the general fund for the operation of public market in compliance with Section 313 of Republic Act No. 7160 and Section 1.3.1 of the Local Manual on Setting up and Operation of Local Enterprises.

We recommended that  the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to:
reclassify the road lots from Land account (1-07-01-010)  to  Infrastructure Assets - Road Network (1-07-03-010)  account  in conformity with COA Circular No. 2015-008;
drop from the Land account and the RPCPPE the lot owned by the Provincial  Government of Cavite with assessed value of P10,800.00 erroneously recorded in the books of accounts of the Municipality;
adjust the recorded value of land and road lots based on acquisition cost and/or fair value as  provided under PPSAS 17 for fair presentation of both  accounts in the financial statements; and
request the assistance of the appraisal committee in establishing the fair value of the two donated lots  at the time of donation for proper recognition in the books of accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct:
the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of all  assets owned by the Municipality to ascertain their existence;
the General Services Officer and Municipal Accountant  to continue their efforts in reconciling their respective records to establish the reliability of the  balances of the PPE accounts  reflected in the financial statements.

We recommended that the  Municipal Mayor direct:
the Municipal Assessor to coordinate with the Bureau of Internal Revenue (BIR) and the Cavite Provincial Treasurer’s Office to determine the amount of taxes due and the possibility of entering into compromise agreement  as to payment of penalties and surcharges;
the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to ensure that the Deed of Sale provides for the payment of taxes  and other expenses related thereto and that all other pertinent documentary requirements for the titling of lands are promptly processed and submitted to the BIR and Register of Deeds, respectively;
the Municipal Budget Officer to allocate funds for the titling of lands owned by the Municipality;
the Municipal Assessor and General Services Officer to facilitate the immediate transfer of title of the  4 procured  lots and  2 donated lots in the name of the Municipality; and
the General Services Officer to take custody of the CTCs and other documents pertaining to land owned by the Municipality and be responsible for its safekeeping.
We also recommended that an investigation be conducted to determine if there are local officials who had been negligent in ensuring payment of taxes and other expenses within the prescribed period and hold them personally liable for the amount of penalties and charges for late payment thereof.
Further, we recommended that copies of the TCTs be presented to the Audit Team for verification/confirmation.
